<ce:para>The use of metallic materials in hydrogen storage and purification demands not only a significant solubility of hydrogen in a these materials but ideally also rapid diffusion by hydrogen in the bulk. To develop suitable hydrogen storage materials, a detailed knowledge of the microscopic mechanisms of hydrogen motion in these systems is required. Density Functional Theory-based methods were used to describe the contributions of activated hopping and quantum tunneling to hydrogen diffusion in ZrX<inf>2</inf> (X = V, Cr, Mn, Fe, and Co) in the C15 Laves phase structure. The predicted self diffusivity of H in ZrCr<inf>2</inf> both with and without tunneling contributions showed that harmonic transition state theory alone was incompatible with the complete set of experimental data. However, including tunneling corrections accurately captured the change in apparent activation energy that was observed as T was varied. The pre-exponential factor associated with diffusion was overestimated by the computational methods, while the predicted activation energies were in good agreement with experiment. At room temperature and above, tunneling contributions were negligible in all materials. However, at temperatures lower than 200 K, tunneling contributions became increasingly dominant. As with the case of ZrCr<inf>2</inf>, the theoretical calculations predicted the activation energy of H diffusion with a high degree of accuracy. This is an abstract of a paper presented in the ACS Fuel Chemistry Meeting Fall 2005 (Washington, DC Fall 2005).</ce:para>
